'''Bruce Mahler''' (born September 12, 1950) is an American actor, producer, and writer. He is known for his role as Sgt. Fackler in the comedy films ''[[Police Academy (franchise)|Police Academy]]'', and as Rabbi Kirschbaum on the sitcom ''[[Seinfeld]]''.
==Biography== He was born on September 12, 1950 in [[Manhattan, New York City]]..
In 1977, Mahler appeared on two episodes of the TV series, ''[[Fernwood 2 Night]]''. In 1980, he appeared on ''[[Fridays (TV series)|Fridays]]'', an early 1980s sketch show on ABC modeled after NBC's ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', where most of Mahler's appearances showcased his musical talent and radio DJ-style voice, most notably in the recurring sketches "The Latin DJ" and the one-off sketches "K.P.L.O" (about Palestine Liberation Organization terrorists hosting a radio show in their bunker) and "A Classical Get-Down" (about a classical pianist who hosts his radio show like a Top 40 station).
Two years after ''Fridays'' was cancelled, Mahler portrayed Sgt. Douglas Fackler in the 1984 film ''[[Police Academy (film)|Police Academy]]''. Other film work included 1984's ''[[Friday the 13th: The Final Chapter]]'', the 1985 sequel ''[[Police Academy 2: Their First Assignment]]'', the American sitcom ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'', 1986's ''[[Police Academy 3: Back in Training]]'', 1987's ''[[Funland (film)|Funland]]'', and the 1989 sequel ''[[Police Academy 6: City Under Siege]]''.
In the 1990s, appeared on the television series ''[[The Famous Teddy Z]]'' and had a recurring role on ''Seinfeld''. Bruce had minor roles in the movies ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]]'', ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'', and ''[[Loaded Weapon 1]]''. Through 1995–1998, Mahler starred as a rabbi who Elaine befriends on the ''Seinfeld'' episodes "[[The Postponement]]", a deleted scene in "[[The Hot Tub]]", "[[The Serenity Now]]", and "[[The Finale (Seinfeld)|The Finale]]".
